{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17604439","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17604439"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:53:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:53:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15834"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15834","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15834"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8525"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71476"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8525","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8525"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15834"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56985"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7496"},{"type":"tags","id":"8730"},{"type":"tags","id":"8733"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20462"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20466"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71476","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71476"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe human ear develops from several embryological sources. The inner ear structures originate from surface ectoderm, while the middle and external ear components derive from neural crest cells, pharyngeal endoderm, and mesoderm.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the embryological origin of the cochlear duct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Develops from neural crest cells","Develops from pharyngeal endoderm","Forms from mesenchymal mesoderm","Develops from the ventral otocyst","Forms from the dorsal otocyst"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecochlear duct develops from the ventral otocyst\u003C/strong\u003E, which initially forms when the otic placode invaginates from surface ectoderm. Through a series of complex folding events, the ventral portion coils to form the cochlear duct, achieving 2.5 turns by week eight of development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeural crest cells\u003C/strong\u003E contribute to the middle ear ossicles but not the cochlea\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPharyngeal endoderm\u003C/strong\u003E forms the middle ear cavity and Eustachian tube\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMesenchymal mesoderm\u003C/strong\u003E forms the otic capsule surrounding the inner ear but not the cochlear duct\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Edorsal otocyst\u003C/strong\u003E gives rise to the semicircular canals and vestibular apparatus\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe development of the inner ear from ectoderm-derived structures is a key example of how complex organs can form through tissue folding and differentiation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The cochlear duct develops from the ventral portion of the otocyst, which forms from the otic placode.","The cochlea achieves its characteristic 2.5 spiral turns by week eight of development.","Different embryological tissues contribute to specific parts of the ear - ectoderm forms the inner ear, neural crest forms middle ear bones, and endoderm forms the middle ear cavity."],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015.","Helwany M, Arbor TC, Tadi P. Embryology, Ear. In: StatPearls [Online]. Updated 2023 Aug 8. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557588/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56985"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15834"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56985","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56985"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-18T18:17:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-31T21:58:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8525"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71476"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4949","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4949"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc23","name":"Embryology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-13T10: